story.description: Suddenly, German planes start dropping bombs on the people, who hide on the roadsides. When the planes are gone, people go back on the road. Among them, a young couple (Mr and Mrs Fossey), with their five or six-year-old daughter, Paulette (Brigitte Fossey), go back to their car, which doesn't want to start. Other people, bothered by this car in the middle of the road, pushes it outside the road. Paulette's parents take a few suitcases, Paulette takes her black and white puppy, and they all start running away on foot.

sentences: - It's ruined! - I told you not to stop the motor.
- We can't go on with three bags. - We'll stop a car.

story.description: Some more German planes are coming in the sky. Paulette and her parents lie down on the side of the road. A horse, frightened by the planes and the bombs, runs away, breaking one the wheel of its two-wheel cart. Paulette's puppy is also frightened by the noise and runs away on the bridge, with Paulette running behind it and her parents behind her.

The four of them lie down in a nook of the bridge. But a plane machine-gun them and kills the parents and the dog. Paulette is spared. She looks at her parents and doesn't seem to understand exactly what happened. She gets up and goes away with the dead dog in her arms. She moves away to avoid the mad horse still pulling its one-wheel cart.

The «exode» people are back on the road. Paulette is taken by a couple in their fifties, the female (Janine Zorelli) seated on a huge pile of bags and cases in a cart, and the male (Georges Sauval) pulling the cart. The female throws the dead dog in the river. But when the couple starts arguing with other people around them, Paulette gets down from the cart, and then down on the edge of the edge, following her dog floating on the water. She eventually catches it back, and we see the mad horse running behind her across the countryside.

sentences: What are you doing? Do you want to get killed?
As if I'm not burdened enough...
Break my cart and I'll burn your truck!
If you want a fight, the war's somewhere else!
Hold your breath and blow up!

story.description: A bit further, a farmer, Mr Dollé (Lucien Hubert) is working in a field with his wife (Suzanne Courtal), his elder son Georges (Jacques Marin), who seems to be in his early thirties, and his second son Raymond (Pierre Mérovée). His younger son, Michel (Georges Poujouly), aged ten, is taking care of the cows. Michel notices the mad horse entering the field and tells his father.

Georges comes closer to the horse, but, at this very moment, another plane comes flying above them. The horse jumps and kicks Georges in the stomach, and then runs away. Georges falls on the ground moaning and his parents and his brother Raymond carry him back to the farm, while Michel runs after a cow, who has gone away.

sentences: Careful, Georges. It's a warhorse, don't touch it.
- Was he shot? - No, it's this goddam horse.
I said not to touch it.

story.description: The cow walks down to a stream, where it meets Paulette, who starts crying. Michel questions Paulette, who tells him about her dead parents, and her dead dog, which she is still holding. Michel tells her to leave the dog in a bush and help him to bring the cow back to the farm.

sentences: - Are you afraid? - I'm not afraid. Cows aren't scary.
I couldn't, I have my dog.
- What's with your dog? - He's dead.
- Where are you from? - From over there.
He'll whip me if I don't bring back the cow.
Leave your dog... I'll give you another.
- Can he swim? - I don't know. We don't speak.

story.description: Between the Dollé's farm and the neighbor one, the Gouard's farm, there is only a stream and a small wooden bridge. Both families have been fighting for year, they don't even know why anymore. When the children walk in the farmyard, Mr Dollé doesn't even notice them, being too busy chasing the Gouard's dog. He starts arguing with Mr Gouard (André Wasley), and then, walking back to his farm, eventually notices Paulette. Michel tells him who she is. His father doesn't seem too keen on the idea of taking care of the little girl, so Michel says he is going to take her to the Gouard's farm. Which gets Mr Dollé very angry, and he pushes both kids in front of him and inside the farm.

sentences: Will your father let me keep the dog?
What're you doing here, stupid dog?
I'll teach you to be a watchdog.
What did my dog do to you?
Always barking and we've got someone wounded.
You care for the wounded so they'll die sooner.
It's all right for you to kill people.
Who pulled your grandmother out of the water?
She'd drowned when you pulled her out.
No, I got a medal for life saving.
Anyway, I'm sick of hearing about your life-saving medal.
Her father and mother were killed.
What should I do about it?
All right, she'll go to the Gouards.
The Gouards? They'll want another medal.
The Gouards? They'll want another medal.
Come and tell us all about it.

story.description: In the large main room of the farm, Raymond and his older sister Berthe (Laurence Badie) are undressing Georges to put him in bed. Georges notices Paulette and the whole family looks at her, including the youngest of the girls, Renée (Violette Monnier), aged thirteen-fourteen. The girls look at Paulette's dress, the mother gives her a glass of milk, with a fly floating on it, and all of them ask her a lot of questions. Paulette, annoyed by them, pushes them away, and tells discreetly to Michel that she is tired.

sentences: I want material like that for my dress.
I want material like that for my dress.
Really? You'll tell us about the war?
- You saw the bombs? - Where are you from?
- What's your name? - How old are you?
Look at your glass. There's a fly.
You'll scare her crowding her like that.
"The military situation worsened on all fronts

story.description: Raymond then talks about the «exode» people dead on the road. Because of a shortage of coffins, they had to be buried in a hole in the ground, «like dogs». His father shuts him up, because he is afraid that Paulette is not quite asleep and may hear what he says. The mother, along with Berthe, Renée and Michel, brings Paulette in the attic, where a bed has been set for her, while the father sits on Georges' bed to read the paper to him.

sentences: They can't even bury them properly.
If you die now you don't even get a box!
Did you see it: "A German side-car was captured"...
She's so clean she'll never get used to it here.
You want to keep her, don't you?

story.description: Later in the night, the whole Dollé family is asleep except Georges, because of the pain in his stomach. Paulette has a nightmare and starts yelling. Georges throws a box on Michel to wake him up. Michel takes a petrol lamp to check on Paulette, who is already half-asleep when Michel reaches the attic. Michel walks back down and reads the paper to Georges to keep him company.

sentences: - What is it? - Don't you hear her?
- What? - I don't want her to cry out.
See, I told her. She's asleep.
If you wish, I won't either.
Want me to read you the paper?
No, not the war, the serial.
"It was still too soon to give the signal to leave.
"Nonetheless, some who were travelling on horseback"...
- You're not up yet? - I'm dressing.
Quiet, you can see he's ill!

story.description: Next morning, the whole family is having breakfast, except Paulette, who is still getting dressed in the attic. She walks down and inquires about the crucifix above Georges' bed. We understand that Paulette's family were atheists, which doesn't seem to please the Dollé, who are good catholics. Mrs Dollé also talks about mentioning Paulette to the gendarmes (the French country police).

sentences: See, I told her. She's asleep.
If you wish, I won't either.
Want me to read you the paper?
No, not the war, the serial.
"It was still too soon to give the signal to leave.
"Nonetheless, some who were travelling on horseback"...
- You're not up yet? - I'm dressing.
Quiet, you can see he's ill!
Yes, but I never knew who he was.
We should find out where she's from. Where are you from?
- Poor child. - She should be baptized.
We must tell the mayor or they'll say we stole her...
We should go to the police.
In any case, we must report her.
You take care of your cows.

story.description: Discreetly without Michel seeing her, Paulette finds the place where she left her dog, and, with a hoe, she starts digging a hole to bury it. She is interrupted by the local vicar (Louis Saintève), who, learning who she is, wants to teach her the sign of the cross. But Paulette, who is holding her dog hidden behind her back, doesn't want to do it.

sentences: He's at the hospital because of the bombings.
I don't need a doctor, I need an undertaker.
You can use the old hearse if we fix it up.
Cat got your tongue? Where do you live?
At Mr. Dollé's. Papa and mama are dead.
Poor child. Did you at least say a prayer for them?
I'll teach you. Put your hands like this.
In the name of the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit. Amen.
Don't you want to? Michel will teach you.

story.description: The vicar walks away, and Paulette, hearing Michel call her, takes her hoe and her dog and walks away to an old disused water mill, inside which she starts digging again. Michel joins her and helps her digging. Michel suggests that they create a dead animals cemetery. He climbs up under the roof of the mill to the nest of a old owl, and takes a dead mole from the nest. He digs another tomb for the mole, and tells Paulette they're going to put crosses on each tomb. He has to show atheist Paulette what a cross exactly is. Paulette then puts her broken necklace on her dog's cross.

sentences: I looked all over for you.
It's where they put the dead to be together.
Why do they put them together?
But my dog will be all alone.
That's his name, he's an owl.
- Is he mean? - No, he's always asleep.
It's not worth it, it's a hundred years old.
May God receive him into paradise.
In the name of the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit.
If you want... and after, we'll put up crosses.
What did your parents teach you?
- Your necklace is pretty. - It's broken.
But there's a prettier one over your brother's bed.
I'll make better ones with a hammer.

story.description: Later in the evening, Michel is in the attic making crosses with pieces of wood, nails and a hammer, while teaching Paulette her prayers, as the vicar asks him to do.

sentences: What did your parents teach you?
- Your necklace is pretty. - It's broken.
But there's a prettier one over your brother's bed.
I'll make better ones with a hammer.
Darn... I have to start over. You don't know how.
and blessed is Jesus the fruit of thy...
What did we say to Gran?
- "Our Father who art in heaven." - To Gran?

story.description: In the main room, the whole family is gathered round the table to eat the evening soup. Raymond checks on his brother, who is spitting blood. Georges is dying and the family doesn't know what to do about it. The mother says that a prayer would help, but the only one who knows his prayers well is Michel, who is ordered back into the main room.

sentences: I don't want to see you together.
Stay then. You'll go to bed without dinner.
I can't understand him, he's spitting again.
First time I've seen someone spit blood.
- The sheets need washing. - Give him a handkerchief.
- Is that better? - Pat him on the back.
With so many people, we haven't even a little prayer.
Our Father, blessed art thou among women.
Give us our daily bread and blessed is the fruit of thy womb, Jesus.
Pray for us sinners, Thy will be full of grace.
Our Father, Mother of God, give us our... bread!

story.description: Michel, who didn't like being punished, starts mumbling false prayers. When the mother tries to give Georges castor oil, and sees that he doesn't move his lips anymore, the whole family understands he is dead. Michel stops mumbling, kneels down by his brother's bed and says real prayers. Paulette walks near him and, whispering, asks him if he is going to dig a hole for his brother, which horrifies Michel.

sentences: Our Father, blessed art thou among women.
Give us our daily bread and blessed is the fruit of thy womb, Jesus.
Pray for us sinners, Thy will be full of grace.
Our Father, Mother of God, give us our... bread!
Our Father who art in heaven...
- Needs a laxative. - There's castor oil.
If it doesn't help, it won't hurt.
Be reasonable, Georges. At least open your eyes.
- They're closed now. - Maybe he's sleeping!
"Thy will be done on earth as it is in heaven.
"Forgive us our trespasses as we forgive those who trespass against us,
I think so too. He's dead.
Will you dig him a hole?
Are you crazy? He's my brother.

story.description: Next day, Mr Dollé is fixing the floor of his hearse, when Michel notices that the four little wooden crosses are not well fixed on the roof of the hearse. He looks for Paulette to tell her about it, and finds her feeding the chicks.

sentences: If I'd given it to him sooner...
You don't know it would've helped.
Not bad, not bad at all.
Will the crosses stay on up there?
Yes, they will. Need me any more?
Give me a nail and that's it.
Why three? There's only my dog and the mole.

story.description: Early next morning, Francis Gouard (Philippe de Chérisey, known as Amédée) is coming back to his father's farm, in full military uniform, and plays his bugle before he gets in. The Dollé family is having breakfast, and, intrigued by the sound of the bugle, they send Michel to spy on the Gouard farm. Michel takes a basket and a sickle and pretends he is cutting grass for the rabbits.

sentences: Why three? There's only my dog and the mole.
- Gouard's son? - Why? The war's not over.
Look and tell me if it's Francis.
I'll cut the grass for the rabbits.

story.description: Michel walks very close to the Gouard farm window, still pretending he is cutting grass. And he sees Francis telling his father and his two sisters, Marcelle (Fernande Roy) and Jeanne (Denise Péronne), how he left the defeated French army. Michel comes closer to the window, and closer to a cage full of young chicks, which he starts stealing, putting them inside his shirt. Mr Gouard sees him and chases him away.

sentences: No more leaders, no more English.
It's not worth marching forever. Don't touch that.
So I left and here I am.
- In the cavalry, we had horses. - Half-tracks are faster.
- In the cavalry, we had horses. - Half-tracks are faster.
In '18, we didn't need to run.
If you'd had Messerschmidts on your tail, you'd have run.
If you'd had Messerschmidts on your tail, you'd have run.
- You need help? What're you up to? - Cutting grass.
- You need help? What're you up to? - Cutting grass.
- It's not yours. - Papa told me to.

story.description: Michel rushes to the attic, where he shows Paulette the chicks, swearing he didn't kill them.

sentences: - You swear it wasn't you killed them? - No.
I wanted to give them a drink.
Their eyes were closed. I thought: "Maybe they're asleep."
Their teeth were clenched. So I thought: "Maybe they're dead."
It's like that... Are you happy?

story.description: Later in the day, Paulette is picking flowers in a field, when she sees Berthe and Francis flirting in the grass. She moves away to meet Michel, who shows her the crosses he just took off from the hearse, and which Paulette finds ugly.

sentences: Their teeth were clenched. So I thought: "Maybe they're dead."
It's like that... Are you happy?
Yes, I was promoted in battle.
- Who told you I watch the cows? - Michel!
I haven't got the nerve. They're following me.
- I'll say. - Go away, you kids!

story.description: It is Georges' funeral. The hearse stops in front of the church, and the coffin is being carried inside. Everyone follows the coffin, except Mr Dollé, who wants to check the wooden floor of his hearse. He is met by a latecomer cousin, who walks inside the church.

sentences: Do we have to take it inside?
It's because of the bottom plank.
If we keep moving it around...
It was the last one, but it's got "cousin" written on it.
- It's not important. - Yes, it is.
You wouldn't say there's a war on here.
At least he'll have a Christian burial.
- Joseph, you're not going? - In a second.

story.description: Inside the church, Michel and Paulette are more interested by the crosses on the walls than by the funeral ceremony.

sentences: You wouldn't say there's a war on here.
At least he'll have a Christian burial.
- Joseph, you're not going? - In a second.
That'll be good for a bee.

story.description: Outside, Mr Dollé is still fixing his hearse, when the Gouard daughters, crossing the village with their cows, see him and make fun of him. They walk away and Mr Dollé notices the missing crosses on the roof of the hearse. He goes inside the church and asks Michel to come outside with him. Michel feels ill at ease, and tells his father that the crosses could have been stolen by the Gouard, a lie his father seems to believes.

sentences: The hearse broke down, like Francis' half-track.
I told you to check the crosses.
- They held all right. - They've come off.
Look for them on the road.
No, we've not lost them. I'd have noticed.
If they're not lost, someone's taken them.
The bell's ringing, we must go back to pray.

story.description: Back inside the church, Paulette doesn't seem interested by what Michel tells her about his father, but more interested by the big copper cross above the altar.

sentences: He saw there are no more crosses. I said it was the Gouards.

story.description: Meanwhile, Francis and his father are sawing wood inside a barn. Mr Gouard says that he doesn't know how Mr Dollé is going to manage his farm without Georges, and Francis answers him there is still Berthe, whom his father calls a hooker. The argument heats up, and Francis says he will marry Bethe, whether his father likes it or not.

sentences: I would have gone to the funeral if I'd known.
All the same, they've got problems...
Who have they got left now?
There's Berthe, she's a good worker.
You should've defended France with your iron horses.
You should've defended France with your iron horses.
You'd have to be in cavalry to be that dull.
Well, if all the horses in the cavalry kicked you,
- it'd clear your head. - Don't speak to me like that!
I'll marry Berthe, you hear me?

story.description: The funeral ceremony is now over and the hearse enters the churchyard, where Michel and Paulette are fascinated by the crosses. While he is shoveling earth on the buried coffin, Mr Dollé tells the vicar about Gouard stealing the crosses of the hearse, but the vicar doesn't seem to believe it.

sentences: A few words to a family that is seeing very hard times.
And that one for a giraffe.
- He's in for us. - They say I'm a deserter.
- Why is he in for you? - He's jealous.
That's no reason to steal the crosses.
When I was fixing the hearse,
Francis is more a deserter than me.
I'll kick his guts out if he keeps it up.
But they have no respect at all.

story.description: Meanwhile, Berthe is telling the vicar she already had sex with Francis, and, since they do want to marry, she asks the priest to fix things with both their families. The vicar can't answer because of the booming noise made by Michel falling down while trying to steal the cross. He rushes out of the confessional, kicks Michel out of the church and pushes Berthe back into the confessional.

sentences: Certainly, but you put the cart before the horse.
We just don't dare tell our parents...
You haven't even finished your penance and you start over!
It doesn't concern you. Go back in, we're not done.

story.description: In the evening, Mr Dollé tells his wife the conversation he had with his neighbor Gouard, who swore he didn't steal the crosses on his wife's tomb. We learn two things, one that Mr Gouard is a widower, two that he neglects his wife's tomb.

sentences: It doesn't concern you. Go back in, we're not done.
I said: "Now you steal crosses from hearses?"
"As to the crosses, I swear on my wife's grave."
"As to the crosses, I swear on my wife's grave."
Let me finish... That's what I said.
I said: "You have no right to swear on her grave."
It's not a grave, it's a slum.
Swear all you want on her grave, it'd be better to clean it.

story.description: In a corner of the main room, Michel is writing cards to put on the animals' tombs (dog, mole, worm, etc.). With his dip pen, he kills a cockroach, which makes Paulette cry.

sentences: Why weren't they at the funeral? That proves it.
- No one told him. - Maybe they didn't know.
They knew even if they weren't told.
I'm fed up with his bugle.
It's not a bugle, it's a trumpet.
Whatever it is, he's still a deserter.
We need two, since there are two graves.
We need two, since there are two graves.
It's not me, it's a bomb. Are you crazy?
Don't kill them! Don't kill them!
They must be dead to bury them.
- I won't talk to you. - Idiot!
Anyway, you promised me the priest's cross.
- A doll's hand. - I don't want it.

story.description: Mr Dollé sends everyone in bed. Paulette kisses everybody around, including Michel, who reminds her that the vicar hit him when he tried to steal the cross. When Paulette is in bed in the attic, she asks Michel to go and steal the crosses in the churchyard.

sentences: - What are you doing? - Finished kissing everyone?
- What you said about the cross. - You didn't give it to me.
I said, get to bed. The time for kisses is over!
I know a place with crosses.
But if the dead grab me by the feet?
- Shall I come up? - I'll come down.
It's a joke, they're not scary.
What does that mean, "cart before the horse"?

story.description: Later in the night, Berthe and Francis are flirting in the hay-barn, but they are interrupted by Paulette and Michel coming to get a wheelbarrow to carry the crosses. Francis hides in the hay, but Michel sees his feet sticking out.

sentences: It's a joke, they're not scary.
What does that mean, "cart before the horse"?
I've never heard it called that.
It's a rocket. Close your eyes.
I can't see if I close my eyes.
- And you? - Is it any of your business?
- A wheelbarrow at this hour! - We're going to get snails.

story.description: The Dollé family reaches the churchyard and finds there are no more crosses on Georges' tomb. The father, who thinks he knows who did it, rushes toward Mrs Gouard's tomb, from which he snatches and breaks the cross. Mr Gouard walks to him and both men first insult each other, then they start fighting and finally they fall into a freshly dug tomb, where they keep on fighting. Berthe runs to the church to get the vicar, who explains to both families who is stealing the crosses. Michel runs away from the churchyard, with both families running after him.

sentences: Just a hole. It's not there.
Just a hole. It's not there.
- You're quite a sight! - Did you hurt yourself?
Joseph, watch out, he's a bad one.
This is no place for a fight.
Aren't you ashamed, you family men!
- He stole Georges' cross. - I don't rob the dead.
I know the one who steals crosses. He tried to steal the altar cross.

story.description: Inside the old mill, Michel has completed his animals' cemetery, with the crosses and the cards naming each animal. Satisfied by his work, he quietly eats an apple.

sentences: If he's not home, he's scared of you.

story.description: From the barn, Michel climbs into the attic, where he doesn't find Paulette, who is being questioned by Berthe about the crosses. Michel, hidden in the staircase leading to the attic, follows the conversation, and when he feels that Paulette is ready to talk, he whispers to Berthe that, if she tells their father about him, he will tell their father about Berthe flirting with Francis in the barn.

sentences: You never could count! Wait till I find him.
Yes, you do. Your nose is twitching.
- Why? - It twitches when you lie.
Rob his brother's cross! Is that nice?
I didn't ask you to cry. I asked where they are.
What were they for? They're not toys.
Until your bottom is black and blue.
So you just have to tell me...
and I'll go get them and it'll be over.
Then why did you get the wheelbarrow from the barn?
- What? - Who you were with in the barn.
- What? - Who you were with in the barn.

story.description: Paulette climbs into the attic, where Michel is waiting for her. He tells her that he can't take her and shows her the animals' cemetery, because his father has locked all the doors.

sentences: I can't see to get undressed.
I'll say good night when you return the crosses.
- To the cemetery. - Not now, it's dark.
Anyway he's looked everything. We'll go tomorrow.
All the crosses and the names!

story.description: Next morning, Paulette wakes up Michel, who is sleeping in the barn. Meanwhile, two gendarmes (André Enard and Bernard Musson), are walking toward the two farms. Francis thinks they're coming to get him, and Raymond thinks they're coming because the Gouard told them about Michel stealing the crosses. Berthe tells her father about Michel being in the barn, and Mr Dollé rushes inside the barn, where he gives his son a good thrashing, while Paulette starts crying.

sentences: I'm going to sleep in the barn.
The Gouards have filed a complaint!
Think it's funny? Are you going to pay for the crosses?
- And that brat's not back! - He's not far.
- Can't you say? - You didn't ask.
- Damn it, the police! - What'll they do to us?
I swear too. Cross my heart and hope to die.
Tell me where the crosses are.
Tell me, you stubborn little brat.
Tell me, you stubborn little brat.
What did you do with the crosses?
What did you do with the crosses?
Fourteen thousand kicks in the pants!
- Let him be! - Can't you see I'm busy?

story.description: Mrs Dollé walks in the barn to explain her husband that the gendarmes only came to take Paulette away. Michel tells his parents that, if Paulette stays with him, he will tell them where the crosses are hidden. But, when the gendarmes walk in the barn, Mr Dollé doesn't keep the promise he made to his son and signs the document the gendarme gives him. Michel runs away and Paulette tells the gendarmes her name is Paulette Dollé (actually, we shall never know her real name).

sentences: - Let him be! - Can't you see I'm busy?
They didn't come for that! It's for Paulette.
They won't hurt her. They'll take her to an orphanage.
- She's not going. - We can't keep her.
If I tell where they are, you'll keep her?
- It's nothing to do with it. - Then you'll never get them, never!
- We'll see. - You won't get them that way.
we'll give the crosses back and apologize to everyone.
And she'll go to catechism and help around the home.
- Tell me where they are. - Promise me.
There she is, the poor thing.
- What's her name? - We call her Paulette.
Your parents were killed in the bombings?
Your parents were killed in the bombings?
- We need the facts. - You'll take her though?
You're going for a ride with these nice men.
I didn't promise, so shut up.
You say that to your father?
He said she could stay if I said where the crosses are.

story.description: Inside the old mill, Michel throws all the crosses in the river, where they are floating away. Then he entrusts Paulette's broken necklace to the old owl.

In the Red Cross refugees center, a nun (Madeleine Barbulé) ties a badge bearing the name of «Paulette Dollé» around Paulette's neck, and asks her to keep it. The nun walks away, and Paulette remains seated on her bench until she hears someone call «Michel». Of course, it is not Michel Dollé, but Paulette runs among the refugees calling «Michel».

sentences: Has she told you her name?
Has she told you her name?
With little girls just like you!
With many sorrows, but very happy all together.
